The gain in screen size, even compared to the standard S10, isn't that big of a deal and cannot justify the overall size and bulk.  I also hate the fact that they changed the UI navigation gestures, the new gestures are hit and miss but that applies to all S24 models.It was a good bundle deal from amazon though who generously threw in the original silicone case besides the galaxy buds fe and the free 2 year screen insurance samsung egypt offers early buyers. The free screen insurance is a little tricky to activate though. You need to log into your samsung members app, discover, tap the benefits tab and select the screen insurance, then manually register for it. The item listed here is the phone ONLY, if you are trying to buy the BUNDLE like I did, it's a different listing and will be clearly titled bundle. Phone and accessories were delivered together the same day. Delivery required a PIN as with all high value items. All items were sealed as expected from amazon, and the phone's warranty card was wedged in the box as usual. This is only for your own assurance, since from experience, you don't need the card for warranty claims as Samsung Egypt can look up the local warranty information if any with the phone's serial number.If you know exactly what you are getting and have used a recent ultra or note phone, go right ahead, you will not be disappointed aside from the new navigation gestures if you use them instead of the buttons like me; but if you are on the fence and trying to decide which S24 model to buy, I suggest you see them in person first. I know I would choose differently if I did. The anti reflective screen glass on the ultra really works but it also diffuses the pixel light and makes the display look a little bit like an LCD backlit display not an OLED. I really recommend you check out the phone in person first before dropping 66K on it. I am not happy with my purchase.

I am coming from an S10 which has served me incredibly well for the past 5 years but I wanted a bigger screen because my sight isn't what it used to be. I was between the Ultra and the plus and decided to go with the ultra for the snapdragon and the anti glare display, but now I regret not going with the regular 24 and saving 20K in the process. The gain in screen size, even compared to the standard S10, isn't that big of a deal and cannot justify the overall size and bulk.  I also hate the fact that they changed the UI navigation gestures, the new gestures are hit and miss but that applies to all S24 models.It was a good bundle deal from amazon though who generously threw in the original silicone case besides the galaxy buds fe and the free 2 year screen insurance samsung egypt offers early buyers. The free screen insurance is a little tricky to activate though. You need to log into your samsung members app, discover, tap the benefits tab and select the screen insurance, then manually register for it. The item listed here is the phone ONLY, if you are trying to buy the BUNDLE like I did, it's a different listing and will be clearly titled bundle. Phone and accessories were delivered together the same day. Delivery required a PIN as with all high value items. All items were sealed as expected from amazon, and the phone's warranty card was wedged in the box as usual. This is only for your own assurance, since from experience, you don't need the card for warranty claims as Samsung Egypt can look up the local warranty information if any with the phone's serial number.If you know exactly what you are getting and have used a recent ultra or note phone, go right ahead, you will not be disappointed aside from the new navigation gestures if you use them instead of the buttons like me; but if you are on the fence and trying to decide which S24 model to buy, I suggest you see them in person first. I know I would choose differently if I did. The anti reflective screen glass on the ultra really works but it also diffuses the pixel light and makes the display look a little bit like an LCD backlit display not an OLED. I really recommend you check out the phone in person first before dropping 66K on it. I am not happy with my purchase.

The performance is indistinguishable in day to day usage when compared to SD 8 Gen 3 on a OnePlus 12 with UFS 4.0. Even though the 12R has a UFS 3.1 storage, you are unlikely to notice any difference whatsoever without running benchmarks or checking the specifications. In real life day to day usage, I have not found any difference and I am a power user who uses a lot of applications and use the phone over 8 Hours a day.- The vapour chamber handles the cooling very well which keeps the device at excellent temperature even when playing games for an extended duration. It almost never goes over 38c.- The display has the same features as the OnePlus 12 (the resolution is relatively lower but it's not noticeable to the naked eye without magnification) and this is one of the best displays that you will come across. The HDR performance is also some of the best I have seen and it is a completely different experience. This can also be seen in the HDR shots taken with cameras. I'd suggest going to a OnePlus experience center and searching for 12K HDR videos on YouTube to get a better idea. Note that the 4,500 nits mentioned is only the HDR brightness at a small white portion of the display under sunlight. This is NOT the max brightness of the full display. But it is bright enough to use under direct sunlight.- Battery life is very impressive with over 8 hours of SOT and the 100W included charger fully charges it in about 35 mins.- Also love that the display can be used even when your hands are wet unlike most other smartphones- The bezels are extremely slim and the chin is smaller than the one on the OnePlus 12. I do wish it was equal all around though.Rather than cons, I'll just mention what it lacks.- Wireless charging- Telephoto cameraThat's pretty much it. If you are looking for a smooth and reliable device with solid performance, battery life, fast charging, decent cameras and display experience, I would easily recommend this. Sure the cameras may not be as good as an iPhone 15 (81k) or a Pixel 8 (83k) but they also cost around 80% more than the OnePlus 12R.
